WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.160
All right. Well, thank you for being here. I'm excited to talk to you today about RStudio

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:15.880
Connect. I want to talk to you a little bit about where the product's been. I'm going

00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:19.639
to unveil a few things that we've been working on in recent months today. And then I want

00:00:19.639 --> 00:00:22.600
to talk to you about where we're going in the future.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:29.360
But I'm going to do this through a vehicle that's a little bit unorthodox. So just between

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:34.520
us, and this doesn't leave this room, I've been working on a little side hustle called

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:41.160
Hats4Cats.me. This is outside of my role at RStudio. And basically, Hats4Cats is all about

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:46.080
addressing the booming market of cat owners who need headwear for their pets.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:49.480
And so one of the things that we've been trying to work on here, we've raised a round of funding,

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:53.400
hired a data science team, and I kind of got a front row seat to sort of our experience

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:57.240
using R there and sort of what that looked like. And so I thought I'd share that with

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:02.080
you today and see if any of that resonates with kind of how your journey.

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:07.080
So things started off really great. Everyone was in R. We had two data scientists originally.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:12.239
They were both using R. And they both installed R just recently when they got started. They

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:16.440
were using the latest versions of R packages. And everything was just fine.

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:20.120
There were only a handful of artifacts that they produced. So they had a couple R Markdown

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:23.360
reports. We had one Shiny app. Everybody knew where everything was. And so there wasn't

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:28.440
really any ambiguity. And we were all using the latest versions of everything. So everything

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:31.879
just worked out fine. But pretty quickly, things went downhill.

00:01:31.879 --> 00:01:35.199
So after about four or five months, we had enough content now that people started getting

00:01:35.199 --> 00:01:39.080
confused about where does this report live? Where does this Shiny app live? And our data

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:42.480
scientists were spending all their days not actually doing data science, but answering

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:45.879
these requests about can you send me this report? Can you rerun this report to get this

00:01:45.879 --> 00:01:50.519
week's data? Or can you run this report just for my product?

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:53.120
And so they spend all their time doing these menial tasks instead of doing the stuff that

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:57.040
we really want them to do, which is unlocking value by tapping into and exploring the data

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:00.800
that we have. Secondly, it was all irreproducible. So we

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:04.800
started having problems where one analyst would send the other analyst some code, and

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:07.800
they weren't able to run it successfully. Or they would go to rerun something that they'd

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:12.119
run six months ago. And all of a sudden, nothing works because some package changed. And so

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:15.119
they'd spend all day fixing this thing that should have taken five minutes.

00:02:15.119 --> 00:02:18.759
And the content is spread all over. So we have dozens of reports now. They're on our

00:02:18.759 --> 00:02:23.520
network share. They're on Slack. They're trickling around in email. And nobody knows

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:29.039
where anything is, which creates a huge problem. And then lastly, we had some issues with security.

00:02:29.039 --> 00:02:32.720
We had, at a couple of occasions, we had some sensitive financial reports that ended up

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:36.639
on a network share that were accessible to the whole company, which nobody wants.

00:02:36.639 --> 00:02:40.119
But we solved these problems with RStudio Connect. And so I'll talk to you a little

00:02:40.119 --> 00:02:43.080
bit about that. If you're unfamiliar, RStudio Connect is a

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:47.039
content hub and execution engine for your data products. And so what that specifically

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:51.080
means as an analyst is that your first experience is going to be clicking a little Publish

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:55.539
button in the RStudio IDE, which I'll show you. And that will do all the hard work of

00:02:55.539 --> 00:03:00.000
getting your content from your computer onto the remote machine.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.800
You can schedule and distribute our markdown content. And so now you get an easier way

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:09.460
to be able to operationalize some of the content that you've produced. You can handle the kind

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:13.119
of scaling problems that we've been discussing about all morning around Shiny applications

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:18.559
to be able to send more and more traffic towards Shiny or Plumber APIs that you've deployed.

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:21.440
And one of the more important features, you can manage access controls. And so you can

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:26.699
actually go in and say, these users or these groups should be able to access this report,

00:03:26.699 --> 00:03:28.839
but nobody else is going to be able to see it.

00:03:28.839 --> 00:03:32.139
And an important caveat, this is an on-premises commercial application. So this is not one

00:03:32.139 --> 00:03:36.100
of our open source contributions, but this is something that you can purchase and run

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:40.820
inside your firewall on-premises. And so this will integrate with your directory of users

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:43.699
and groups and all that kind of stuff.

00:03:43.699 --> 00:03:48.500
So a couple things that I'm excited to announce today that are available in the 1.7.0 release.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:51.699
First of all, it's programmatic deployment. And so most people tend to reach for the push

00:03:51.699 --> 00:03:55.940
button deployment from the RStudio IDE. But you also have the option now of saying, if

00:03:55.940 --> 00:04:01.500
you want to point your Jenkins or your Bamboo server at a Git repo and have it monitor that

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:05.820
and automatically pull down changes and publish those, you now have that option with the programmatic

00:04:05.820 --> 00:04:06.779
deployment.

00:04:06.779 --> 00:04:09.660
We have customizable email, if you haven't seen this yet. So you can go in and you can

00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:15.500
tailor the body of an email or the message, as Tarif showed this morning. And lastly,

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:18.899
we have content instrumentation, or metrics, around your content. So you can see who's

00:04:18.899 --> 00:04:23.739
viewing your content when. And then you can go in and use that data to develop reports

00:04:23.739 --> 00:04:27.299
or answer questions like, what is the most important content? What should I be maintaining?

00:04:27.299 --> 00:04:29.899
Where should I be putting my energy?

00:04:29.899 --> 00:04:37.779
So let me show you a quick demo of what that looks like. So let's actually start in the

00:04:37.779 --> 00:04:43.140
RStudio IDE. And what I have here is just a kind of run-of-the-mill R Markdown report.

00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:47.179
So I can knit this locally. And the original workflow that our data scientists were using

00:04:47.179 --> 00:04:53.679
is that they would do some analysis. And then they would render it locally on their desktop.

00:04:53.679 --> 00:04:57.579
And then they'd go in and say, for this week's sales, we're going to copy this image out

00:04:57.579 --> 00:05:02.540
into an email or copy it into a PowerPoint and send that over to our executives.

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:06.980
So it's a lot of kind of manually operating on this data. And they spend a lot of their

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:11.420
time just kind of hand-crafting these reports, rerunning these things every day.

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:16.260
So the better alternative that I'll suggest today is you click this Publish button here.

00:05:16.260 --> 00:05:20.260
And that allows you to send up the relevant files that you're working with, any data that

00:05:20.260 --> 00:05:23.700
you're using locally. And you can publish that over to RStudio Connect. And what's going

00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:26.700
to happen behind the scenes is it's going to capture all of the code that you're using

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:31.619
in this report. And then additionally, it's going to build a manifest of all the packages

00:05:31.619 --> 00:05:34.320
that you're using and even the versions of those R packages.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:38.480
And so now you get all of that that's happening here. And then that's going to get recreated

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:43.519
identically on the server. And so now you have no kind of lack of parity between your

00:05:43.519 --> 00:05:46.920
local experience and what's going to run on the server. And so lo and behold, I now have

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:52.279
this RStudio Connect report that looks just like what it looked like on my desktop and

00:05:52.279 --> 00:05:55.500
is using the same packages, the same version of R, et cetera.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:59.559
Now what's exciting about this is that now I have a URL that I can use to just send other

00:05:59.559 --> 00:06:03.519
collaborators. And they can now see the same report without any work on their part or any

00:06:03.519 --> 00:06:07.640
installing of software or anything like that. Secondly, you've got these access controls

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:11.320
over here. So I can now lock down who should be able to view this report. Maybe it's just

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:14.600
me. Maybe I want to make it public. Or maybe everybody in the organization should be able

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:19.760
to see it. And then because it's in our markdown report, I can also schedule this to repeat.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:23.100
And so maybe I want this report to run every week. Let's say I want it to run every Monday

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:27.480
morning and then perhaps even send an email out once it's done to the executives who are

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:31.119
interested in this report. And so all that now is going to happen for free. And what's

00:06:31.119 --> 00:06:34.880
great is that if there's ever a problem with this report, if there's an issue running it,

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:37.320
I'm going to get an email saying, hey, your report had a problem. You should go check

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:40.920
it out. And so now I don't have to think about this anymore. And I can just schedule this

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:45.359
report once and then leave it running. So this is pretty exciting. But we can actually

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:50.519
go one step further. And so Tarif alluded to a concept this morning called parameterized

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:55.160
R markdown. And I'm curious, how many of you have used parameterized R markdown yet? OK.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:58.519
So a decent number of you. So parameterized R markdown is actually a concept that you

00:06:58.519 --> 00:07:01.440
can use locally. And so I'd encourage you all to try this. It's a pretty handy way to

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:06.279
just kind of define a set of parameters that you want to put into an R markdown report.

00:07:06.279 --> 00:07:10.820
And then you can actually just go through and leverage those parameters to kind of tailor

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:14.559
the report to the experience that you want. And so within the IDE, you just click this

00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:17.920
knit with parameters button. And now I can go in and I can say, rather than just running

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:23.279
a weekly report, maybe I want to run a report for a particular product in our line or a

00:07:23.279 --> 00:07:27.799
different number of days for the historical data. And now I can go through and knit that.

00:07:27.799 --> 00:07:30.839
And then I just get the local report here that has the data that I want.

00:07:30.839 --> 00:07:34.760
So this would be at least a step up for you if you have people coming back and repeatedly

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:38.679
saying, I want this report but slightly modified. This gives you a way to handle one source

00:07:38.679 --> 00:07:44.559
code, one bit of one report that you need to maintain, but still be able to create things

00:07:44.559 --> 00:07:48.200
for your users that they're interested in. But even better, if you deploy this on RStudio

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:52.440
Connect, you actually get this little input tab on the left. And that allows other users

00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:56.559
who haven't installed R, who haven't installed RStudio, who are not scientists, to go in

00:07:56.559 --> 00:08:01.279
and be able to specify those parameters themselves. And so now I can say that same report for

00:08:01.279 --> 00:08:06.040
30 days, cowboy hat. I can run that report, and I can just get the data that I'm interested

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:11.200
in. Even better, this is a full-fledged report on Connect. And so I can kind of hop around

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:15.559
and view different reports here that I've previously configured and saved. And then

00:08:15.559 --> 00:08:19.279
if I want to schedule these or even distribute these automatically, I can do that.

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:23.320
And so now I have one R Markdown document that I'm maintaining, one bit of source code

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:28.079
that I've worked on. And yet, all these people are able to kind of get the customized, tailored

00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:31.559
views that they're interested in, that they can even define themselves without me having

00:08:31.559 --> 00:08:35.719
to be involved at all. So this is a huge step up.

00:08:35.719 --> 00:08:43.119
And then Connect also can support your Shiny applications and your plumber APIs. So this,

00:08:43.119 --> 00:08:48.119
I usually wouldn't show sensitive financial data at my company here, but I think we're

00:08:48.119 --> 00:08:52.200
all friends, so I'll show this to you. So you can go back, and this is a little dashboard

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:56.679
that we would share internally. We've got a big monitor in our office that kind of shows

00:08:56.679 --> 00:09:01.200
this. And I think there might be a bug or something in this report.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:07.400
But basically, you can kind of see how the company's doing and how things look. So you've

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:10.919
got all the normal toggles that you want with Shiny to be able to host that and let people

00:09:10.919 --> 00:09:14.400
interact with it. Again, the same access controls and everything that you'd want there.

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:19.520
But even better with Shiny now, I can go in and I can scale out processes to handle the

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:24.119
capacity that I'm expecting. Or even, as Joe was alluding to earlier, we can also handle

00:09:24.119 --> 00:09:27.440
clustered environments for our Studio Connect. So if you were here last year, you might have

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:31.719
seen Sean Lopp give the demonstration of having 10,000 concurrent users on a Shiny application

00:09:31.719 --> 00:09:38.080
using our Studio Connect. So there's really, you can handle pretty broad scale of incoming

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:40.640
content here. And then lastly, we have the same thing around

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:45.039
plumber APIs for using plumber. We can easily host those, and you get all the same scaling

00:09:45.039 --> 00:09:49.359
and tuning parameters that you'd expect with Shiny to be able to define how responsive

00:09:49.359 --> 00:09:52.719
you need this to be and what sort of load you'd expect.

00:09:52.719 --> 00:09:59.559
All right. So let's hop back to the slides. So that's really everything that I want to

00:09:59.559 --> 00:10:03.719
show you around R. But there's one more topic that I want to address before in our time

00:10:03.719 --> 00:10:07.520
together, and that is Python. So this has come up already a couple times on this track.

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:12.200
But one of the things that we did at Hats for Cats is we hired a data analyst that was

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:16.919
using Python. And so historically, it was pretty difficult to integrate together, right?

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:21.200
You've kind of got these two different languages that they don't interoperate all that well.

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:24.159
This has improved a lot recently with the reticulate package. And so if you haven't

00:10:24.159 --> 00:10:28.760
seen this, reticulate is a way for you to invoke and interact with your Python code

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:32.760
using R. And so this got a lot better, and we were kind of able to find some ways to

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:35.919
work together. But there was still this open question of what are we going to do when it

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:41.599
comes time to publish? So we had this great publishing and operationalization system for

00:10:41.599 --> 00:10:46.239
our R content in RStudio Connect that we lack with Python. And so I'm excited to announce

00:10:46.239 --> 00:10:51.039
today we now have Python support in RStudio Connect.

00:10:51.039 --> 00:10:59.440
So specifically, this looks like two different features. So first of all, you have what Tareef

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:06.159
showed this morning, which is RSConnect and the RStudio IDE now capture the Python dependencies

00:11:06.159 --> 00:11:10.200
and the Python packages that you have locally before you deploy. So if you are using reticulate

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:14.359
in your R content and you go to publish, you'll get the same experience with your Python

00:11:14.359 --> 00:11:20.239
packages that you're used to with your R packages. But even more exciting, in my opinion, is

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:23.679
we now have a Jupyter Notebook plugin, which allows you to publish directly from your Jupyter

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:27.440
Notebooks. You get the exact same push-button publishing experience that you have in the

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:32.840
RStudio IDE with your R content you now have in Jupyter Notebooks with Python.

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:39.559
So I'll show you this real quick. So the motivating feature here is in Hats for Cats, a lot of

00:11:39.559 --> 00:11:43.200
our customers would say, look, I know what your hat looks like. I can see that picture

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:46.280
online and I know what my cat looks like, but I can't always envision what they would

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:51.039
look like together. And so we wanted to do some engineering to solve this problem. So

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:55.679
first of all, we hopped into a Jupyter Notebook and we did some exploration to say how effective

00:11:55.679 --> 00:12:01.599
can we be at detecting faces in a given image? And so this is a Jupyter Notebook that I have

00:12:01.599 --> 00:12:08.559
here, which our Python analyst produced using all Python code. And I click this publish

00:12:08.559 --> 00:12:11.440
button in the Jupyter Notebook and I get that same experience of being able to send

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:16.080
this code over into RStudio Connect. And you'll see that it's doing all the same kind of intelligent

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:20.000
features that we had in R around looking at the version of Python that we're using, the

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.080
versions of the different packages, and then it sends it up to connect. And now I click

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:28.559
this button and I can see, as you can see, I didn't have it rendered locally, but this

00:12:28.559 --> 00:12:32.880
actually rendered on the server. And so you get kind of, you know, the full abilities

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:36.679
of your server here and that entire environment was recreated so that I get the exact same

00:12:36.679 --> 00:12:40.640
experience locally as I get remotely. And then you get all the same bells and whistles

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:44.159
that you have with our markdown content in terms of being able to schedule this, rerun

00:12:44.159 --> 00:12:49.919
it, email it, et cetera. One other feature then around Python is if

00:12:49.919 --> 00:12:54.960
you wanted to use this in a reticulated way, then you can do that as well. And so we have

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:58.520
the Jupyter Notebook. We've proven that we have kind of a validation of our technology.

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:02.440
And so now we know, okay, we can detect faces effectively. But one of the things that we

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:06.479
now want to do is we want to operationalize this. And we have, you know, a great ability

00:13:06.479 --> 00:13:09.880
to do that with an R, as you've seen through Plumber or through Shiny. There are a lot

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:13.760
of great ways for you to take your R code and get it into the hands of your users. And

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:17.479
so one of the things we wanted to do was actually build a Shiny app that uses the Python code

00:13:17.479 --> 00:13:22.159
on the back end to do the image detection. So Python has some really strong image processing

00:13:22.159 --> 00:13:27.000
libraries, specifically OpenCV. And so we wanted to continue using Python for what Python

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.119
is good for, but use R for what R is good for. And so develop a Shiny application that

00:13:31.119 --> 00:13:36.119
allows us to kind of blend those two. And so here we put together just kind of a preview

00:13:36.119 --> 00:13:40.119
of what that's going to look like that we can host on our page. So this is a Shiny application

00:13:40.119 --> 00:13:44.400
with a little webcam widget input. And now I can envision what it's going to look like

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:48.159
for me to purchase any of these different hats for my cat. I unfortunately don't have

00:13:48.159 --> 00:13:53.440
a cat up here with me, so you'll have to use your imagination. But right, so now you get

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:56.760
the kind of same capabilities that you would expect around being able to operationalize

00:13:56.760 --> 00:14:05.000
your content, whether or not it's using Python under the hood.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.200
All right. So a little bit about what's next. One of the things that we're working on is

00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:11.679
called SAML. If you don't know what that means, just skip it. But if you do, that might excite

00:14:11.679 --> 00:14:16.679
you. This is a new way to kind of authenticate users into an organization that your IT people

00:14:16.679 --> 00:14:19.840
may be excited about. We're also working on the job launcher integration. And so you've

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:22.840
probably heard a couple of references to this. But the basic premise is that we want to be

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:26.960
able to run R in other environments rather than just the local server where Connect is

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:30.640
installed. So if you're using Kubernetes, or if you're using Slurm, or some other kind

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:34.960
of compute bucket, we'll be able to distribute our R processes there so that you can see

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:39.840
them and run them there. We're also working on formal Git integration. So being able to

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:45.440
use Git kind of as a first-class citizen within Connect so that you point at a GitHub repository,

00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:49.119
we'll monitor that repository for changes, pull down any changes that come in, and automatically

00:14:49.119 --> 00:14:53.919
deploy it. You also get an improved view of scheduled content. And so you can see what

00:14:53.919 --> 00:14:59.200
processes are scheduled to run when and who's scheduled what kind of work to run. You can

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:02.760
get customizable views into content. So we've heard from a lot of people, especially consultants,

00:15:02.760 --> 00:15:07.400
who say, I want a kind of branded portal for my customers. I don't want to show your logos.

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:11.679
I want to show my logo. And so being able to kind of do that in a way that allows people

00:15:11.679 --> 00:15:14.400
to sort of tailor the different views that they get and the different experiences is

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:20.080
more of kind of a content management system. And then lastly, more Connect server API endpoints.

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:24.799
